<section xml:id="subsubsec-representing-vectors-geometrically" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Representing Vectors Geometrically</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.9 Vectors 1
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </introduction>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Specific Learning Outcome</title>
                <p>Add vectors in different situations</p>
            </li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Grade Level</title>
                <p>Grade 10</p>
            </li>
            <li component="lesson-plan">
                <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                <p>40 minutes</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>By the end of this lesson, learners should be able to:</alert>
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Know:</alert> How vectors are represented geometrically using arrows; that arrow length represents magnitude and the arrowhead shows direction.
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Do:</alert> Draw vectors on a coordinate plane; calculate vector magnitudes using the distance formula; add and subtract vectors algebraically.
        </p>
        <p component="lesson-plan">
            <alert>Apply:</alert> Use geometric vector representation and addition in navigation, physics, and engineering contexts.
        </p>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/representing-vectors-geometrically.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/vectors-1/step-by-step-guide_representing-vectors-geometrically.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Organize students into groups of 2–3.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Materials:</alert> Ruler, graph paper, pencil, calculator.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Guide students to draw vector <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> as an arrow from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,2)</m>.</li>
                <li>Help students apply the distance formula to calculate magnitude.</li>
                <li>For the addition task, ensure <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m> starts where <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> ends (tip-to-tail method).</li>
                <li>For the parallelogram task, demonstrate drawing both vectors from the origin and completing the parallelogram.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Probing Questions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li><q>What does the arrow length represent?</q></li>
                <li><q>Why do we use arrows to represent vectors?</q></li>
                <li><q>How is the magnitude calculated from the components?</q></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Materials: ruler, graph paper, pencil.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw vector <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> from <m>A(0,0) to B(4,2)</m>. Measure its magnitude using the distance formula.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw another vector <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m> from <m>B(4,2)</m> to <m>C(6,5)</m>. Add <m>\overrightarrow{AB}</m> and <m>\overrightarrow{BC}</m> .
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Draw two vectors from the origin: <m>\mathbf{a} = (3,1)</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = (2,4)</m>. Construct the parallelogram to determine <m>\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Compare with other groups and discuss the results.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <insight>
        <p>
             We can represent a vector by a line drawn between two points 
            as shown in <xref ref="repsentation-vec"/> below:
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="repsentation-vec">
            <caption></caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}
                        % Draw an arrow from A to B
                        \draw[|-|] (0,0) -- (4,0) node[right] {Q};
                        
                        % Label points
                        \node[left] at (0,0) {P};
                        
                        % Draw vector
                        \draw [-{Latex[scale=2]}] (2,0) -- (2.1,0); 
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
        <p xml:id="auto_d869dn8u">
            In <xref ref="repsentation-vec"/>, the direction of
            the vector is indicated by an arrow pointing to the right, while
            its magnitude is determined by the length of <m>PQ</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_71m29lzp">
            A vector <m>PQ</m> can be denoted as <m>\underset{\sim}{PQ}</m> or <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m>.The magnitude of vector <m>PQ</m>
            is represented as <m>|PQ|</m>. In this case, we refer to <m>P</m> as <alert>initial point</alert> and <m>Q</m>
            as the <alert>terminal point</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_h6fioij1">
            Additionally, a vector can also be represented using a single small letter,such as  <m>\mathbf{a}</m> or <m>\underset{\sim}{\mathbf{a}}</m>.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction (10 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalize their discoveries with the key concepts in the textbook.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Clarify that arrow length represents magnitude (not just any line).</li>
                <li>Emphasize that the arrowhead shows direction.</li>
                <li>Show that magnitude is always positive (it is a length).</li>
                <li>Connect the distance formula to the Pythagorean theorem.</li>
                <li>Demonstrate that both tip-to-tail and parallelogram methods produce the same resultant.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (15 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Guide students through the worked examples below, then assign independent practice.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teaching Tips:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>For magnitude problems, remind students to find components first, then apply the formula.</li>
                <li>For addition and subtraction, stress that corresponding components are combined separately.</li>
                <li>Encourage students to sketch vectors on graph paper alongside algebraic work.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the magnitude of vector <m>\overrightarrow{PQ}</m> where <m>P(1,2)</m> and <m>Q(5,5)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Step 1: Determine the components.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                \overrightarrow{PQ} = (5-1, 5-2) = (4,3)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Step 2: Use the magnitude formula.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                |\overrightarrow{PQ}| = \sqrt{4^2 + 3^2}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                = \sqrt{16 + 9} = \sqrt{25} = 5
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Add vectors <m>\mathbf{a} = (2,3)</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = (4,1)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Add corresponding components.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} = (2+4, 3+1)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                = (6,4)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the resultant vector is <m>(6,4)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine <m>\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}</m> if 
                <m>\mathbf{a} = (5,2)</m> and 
                <m>\mathbf{b} = (1,4)</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Subtract corresponding components.
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b} = (5-1, 2-4)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                = (4,-2)
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the resulting vector is <m>(4,-2)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket (5 minutes)</title>
        <p>
            Students complete individually to demonstrate understanding.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 1:</alert> Draw a vector from point <m>A(1,1)</m> to point <m>B(4,5)</m> on graph paper. Calculate its magnitude using the distance formula.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 2:</alert> Given vectors <m>\mathbf{p} = (2,3)</m> and <m>\mathbf{q} = (5,1)</m>, find <m>\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Question 3:</alert> Explain why we use arrows to represent vectors. What do the length and direction of the arrow represent?
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q1:</alert> Components: <m>\overrightarrow{AB} = (3, 4)</m>. Magnitude: <m>|\overrightarrow{AB}| = \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{25} = 5</m> units.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q2:</alert> <m>\mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q} = (2+5,\; 3+1) = (7, 4)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Q3:</alert> We use arrows because vectors have both magnitude and direction. The length of the arrow represents the magnitude; the arrowhead shows the direction.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="ex-representing-vectors-geometrically">

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the magnitude of vector <m>(3,4)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    \sqrt{3^2 + 4^2} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25} = 5
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Add vectors <m>(1,2)</m> and <m>(3,5)</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    (1+3, 2+5) = (4,7)
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Given <m>A(0,0), B(2,1)</m>, and <m>C(5,4)</m>, determine 
                    <m>\overrightarrow{AB} + \overrightarrow{BC}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    \overrightarrow{AB} = (2,1)
                    </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    \overrightarrow{BC} = (3,3)
                    </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    (2,1) + (3,3) = (5,4)
                    </m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, <m>\overrightarrow{AB} + \overrightarrow{BC} = (5,4)</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    If <m>\mathbf{a} = (6,-2)</m> and <m>\mathbf{b} = (4,3)</m>, find <m>2\mathbf{a}</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>
                    2\mathbf{a} = (12,-4)
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p>
            <alert>For Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Provide pre-drawn axes and coordinate grids.</li>
                <li>Use colour coding for different vectors.</li>
                <li>Provide step-by-step templates for the distance formula.</li>
                <li>Allow calculators for all magnitude calculations.</li>
                <li>Start with vectors along axes before moving to diagonal vectors.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>For Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>Introduce unit vectors and vector decomposition.</li>
                <li>Challenge with finding vectors given magnitude and direction.</li>
                <li>Connect to trigonometry (angle calculations).</li>
                <li>Introduce the dot product conceptually.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Extension Activity — Vector Art Project:</alert> Students design a shape or pattern using at least 5 vectors on graph paper, label each with coordinates, calculate magnitudes, and colour-code vectors by magnitude range.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</section>